  "name": "K+ as allosteric ligand on a chloride channel (DmAlka)",
  "description": "Drosophila DmAlka (CG12344) is a Cys-loop pentameric ligand-gated anion channel previously labeled an alkaline-activated chloride channel. Shimomura et al. (Nat Commun 17:3453, 2026) showed extracellular K+ binds at the ECD-TMD interface (5 K+ per pentamer, IC50 = 0.645 mM, 4-oxygen coordination, K+-O distance 2.79 Å — matching KcsA filter geometry) and acts as an allosteric mode-switch: K+ binding alters ligand sensitivity, desensitization kinetics, blocker binding, anion selectivity, and HCO3- permeability. The channel SENSES K+ but CONDUCTS Cl-. Engineered human GlyR alpha2 variants (S81D + G83N + N95D + P173Q; or RNA-edited P219L on alpha2B) reproduce K+ sensitivity at ischemic / seizure K+ levels (>50 mM); these variants are upregulated in temporal lobe epilepsy hippocampus.",
